Real-Time Troubleshooting Scenarios
🧠 Scenario 1: Exit Code 137 (OOMKilled)

Situation:
Your pod keeps restarting.

kubectl get pods

Output:

my-app   CrashLoopBackOff
kubectl describe pod my-app

You see:

Reason: OOMKilled
Exit Code: 137
✅ Root Cause:
Container exceeded memory limit
🔧 Fix:
resources:
  requests:
    memory: "256Mi"
  limits:
    memory: "512Mi"

👉 Increase memory OR optimize app memory usage

🧠 Scenario 2: Exit Code 143 (SIGTERM)

Situation:
Pod restarted during deployment.

✅ Root Cause:
Rolling update
Manual pod delete
Autoscaler action
🔧 Fix:

👉 Usually NO issue (expected behavior)

👉 But if app shuts down abruptly:

terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 30
🧠 Scenario 3: Exit Code 1 (App Crash)

Situation:
Pod fails immediately.

kubectl logs my-app

Output:

Database connection failed
✅ Root Cause:
Application error
🔧 Fix:
Check env variables
Check DB connectivity
Fix code/config
🧠 Scenario 4: Exit Code 127 (Command Not Found)

Situation:
Container never starts.

kubectl logs my-app

Output:

sh: python: not found
✅ Root Cause:
Wrong base image OR missing binary
🔧 Fix:
FROM python:3.10

OR correct command in deployment:

command: ["python3", "app.py"]
🧠 Scenario 5: Exit Code 139 (Segmentation Fault)
✅ Root Cause:
Native app crash (C/C++/Java JNI issues)
🔧 Fix:
Debug core dump
Check library compatibility
Update runtime
