🚀 Top 20 Scenario Questions – Perfect Answers
1. CrashLoopBackOff

I check pod details using kubectl describe pod and logs with kubectl logs --previous.
Identify root cause like app crash, config issue, or OOM.
Fix config/resource and redeploy or restart the pod.

2. Exit Code 137

Exit code 137 indicates the container was killed due to OOM.
I confirm using kubectl describe pod and check memory usage.
Increase memory limits or optimize application usage.

3. High Latency (Pods Running)

I check metrics (latency, traffic) and resource usage using kubectl top pods.
Then verify logs and downstream dependencies like DB or APIs.
Mitigate by scaling pods or rolling back recent changes.

4. Pod in Pending State

I check kubectl describe pod for scheduling issues.
Possible causes: insufficient resources, node taints, or PVC issues.
Fix by adding resources, adjusting tolerations, or fixing storage.

5. Service Not Accessible

I verify service and endpoints using kubectl get svc and kubectl get endpoints.
Check pod labels and service selector mismatch.
Also validate network policies and port configuration.

6. App Down After Deployment

I check rollout status and pod health using kubectl rollout status.
Review logs for errors and compare with previous version.
Rollback immediately if issue is from new release.

7. Rollback in Kubernetes

I use kubectl rollout undo deployment <name>.
Rollback when new deployment causes failures or instability.
Always verify rollout history before rollback.

8. New Release Increased Latency

I compare metrics before and after deployment.
Check logs and performance issues in new version.
Rollback or optimize code/config to fix latency.

9. High CPU Usage

I check CPU usage using kubectl top pods.
Identify if due to load or inefficient code.
Scale pods horizontally or optimize application.

10. Sudden Traffic Spike

I validate traffic increase via monitoring tools.
Scale application using HPA or manually increase replicas.
Ensure backend systems can handle increased load.

11. HPA Not Scaling

I check HPA status using kubectl describe hpa.
Verify metrics server and resource requests are configured.
Fix metrics or thresholds to enable scaling.

12. Service Not Reachable (Internal)

I test connectivity using kubectl exec and curl inside pod.
Check service DNS, endpoints, and network policies.
Fix selector or networking issues.

13. Ingress Not Routing

I check ingress rules and controller logs.
Validate service backend and path configuration.
Fix routing rules or ingress controller issues.

14. DNS Not Resolving

I test DNS using nslookup inside pod.
Check CoreDNS pods and config.
Restart or fix DNS configuration.

15. No Logs in kubectl logs

I check if container is running or crashing quickly.
Use --previous flag for crashed containers.
Also verify logging configuration in app.

16. App Slow but No Errors

I check metrics like latency, CPU, and memory.
Analyze dependencies like DB or external APIs.
Use tracing tools to identify bottlenecks.

17. Database Slow

I check DB metrics and connection pool usage.
Identify slow queries or locks.
Optimize queries or scale DB resources.

18. Third-Party API Failure

I check API response and error logs.
Implement retries or fallback mechanisms.
Notify stakeholders and monitor recovery.

19. Production Alert at 2 AM

I validate alert and check impact using dashboards.
Identify root cause using logs, metrics, and events.
Apply quick mitigation and communicate updates.

20. Major Outage

I assess impact and declare incident.
Stabilize system by scaling, rollback, or restarting services.
Perform RCA and implement preventive measures.

